    <h2>When to use this pattern</h2>
    <p>Follow this pattern whenever you need to ask for an NHS number.</p>


    <h2>When not to use this pattern</h2>
    <p>Only ask for NHS numbers if you need them from patients to use the service or if the user is more likely to succeed on the journey if they can provide it.</p>
    <p>Patients do not need to know their NHS number to receive care. This means that the NHS number is not a well-known identifier.</p>
    <p>The National Data Opt-out Programme and NHS Login team found that many users scanning the page can mistake it for their National Insurance number.</p>
    <p>If you need to ask for the NHS number, provide another way to complete the task without it. For example, using a combination of other personal details like a patient's postcode and date of birth.</p>



    <h2>How to use this pattern</h2>
    <p>When asking for an NHS number:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>use a text input that allows for spaces and other characters between numbers. Some users will copy the format the NHS number is printed in (3-3-4) and include spaces.</li>
        <li>give clear guidance on what an NHS number looks like</li>
        <li>allow at least 12 characters in your NHS number input</li>
        <li>add the inputmode='numeric' attribute to your input to provide mobile users with a numeric keyboard on iOS devices and mobile Chrome</li>
        <li>validate the NHS number by using a modulus 11 algorithm to check if the number is valid</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Questions before input</h3>
    <p>Use a two-option radio button that asks the user if they know their NHS number. If they do, route them to a page that asks for their NHS number.</p>
    <p>When asking for their NHS number, use a text input labelled with either "What is your NHS number?" of "Enter your NHS number".</p>
    <p>Provide help text on both pages to help them find their NHS number and confirm they have the right format of number.</p>


